occurrences.line_text: When Scudamour those heauie tydings heard,
To Scudamour, who she had left behind:
Were Britomart, and gentle Scudamour,
Till Scudamour, and that same Briton maide,
At Scudamour, both his professed fone.
But Scudamour then sighing deepe, thus saide,
Now were it not sir Scudamour to you,
Scudamour doth his conquest tell,
That not Scuith guiridh it mote seeme to bee
But rather y Scuith gogh, signe of sad crueltee.
That to the scull a yawning wound it made:
A villaine to them came with scull all raw,
Dead sculs & bones of men, whose life had gone astray.
But all the ground with sculs was scattered,
Some to remoue the scum, as it did rise;
Some scumd the drosse, that from the metall came;
Was ouergrowne with scurfe and filthy scald;
And in his Scutchin bore a Satyres hed:
That bloudie scutchin being battered sore,
With scutchins gilt and banners broad displayd:
That did those armes and that same scutchion weld,
Is wicked Time, who with his scyth addrest,
All whom a Scythian king, that Humber hight,
So she departed, full of griefe and sdaine,
Ne to himselfe, for doubt of being sdayned,
Or rudely sdeigne a gentle harts request;
They sdeigned such lasciuious disport,
But either sdeignes with other to partake:
Nor s'deignfull of so homely fashion,
In sdeignfull wize he drew vnto him neare,
Through vengeful wrath & sdeignfull pride half mad:
Can heart, so plung'd in sea of sorrowes deepe,
A sea of bloud gusht from the gaping wound,
And throw in raging sea with roaring threat.
Out of the sea faire Titans deawy face,
In sea of deadly daungers was distrest;
Yet swimming in that sea of blisfull ioy,
In this wide Inland sea, that hight by name
Who fares on sea, may not commaund his way,
The sea is wide, and easie for to stray;
And calme the sea of their tempestuous spight,
Nor sea of licour cold, nor lake of mire,
Who swelling sayles in Caspian sea doth crosse,
From whence it doth, as cloud from sea arise.
By sea to haue bene fro[m] the Celticke mayn-land brought.
Whom he at sea found wandring from their wayes,
From sea to sea he heapt a mightie mound,
From sea to sea he heapt a mightie mound,
Two dayes now in that sea he sayled has,
With his stiffe oares did brush the sea so strong,
Amid th'AegÃ¦an sea long time did stray,
In the wide sea, they needes must passen by,
It plaine, and by the sea discoloured:
And the great sea puft vp with proud disdaine,
Of huge Sea monsters, such as liuing sence dismayd.
He smote the sea, which calmed was with speed,
That through the sea the resounding plaints did fly:
With that the rolling sea resounding soft,
That seemd the fountaine in that sea did sayle vpright.
His deawy face out of the sea doth reare:
By sea, by land, where so they may be met,
The land to sea, and sea to maineland dry,
The land to sea, and sea to maineland dry,
From where the day out of the sea doth spring,
Shall ouerswim the sea with many one
Huge sea of sorrow, and tempestuous griefe,
All the huge threasure, which the sea below
The sea vnto him voluntary brings,
Which with their finny oars the swelling sea did sheare.
Deepe in the bottome of the sea, her bowre
For Tryphon of sea gods the soueraine leach is hight.
And now she gan approch to the sea shore,
To reach the sea, ere she of him were raught:
For in the sea to drowne her selfe she fond,
So safetie found at sea, which she found not at land.
The land for sea, at randon there to raunge:
But thou good man, sith farre in sea we bee,
Least worse on sea then vs on land befell.
To fetch from sea, that ye at land lost late;
And the wide sea importuned long space
And with a remnant did to sea repaire,
And with him led to sea an youthly trayne,
To seeke her endlong, both by sea and lond.
Ouer the sea, suspended dreadfully,
That filleth all the sea with fome, diuydes
As when two warlike Brigandines at sea,
He sends the sea his owne with double gaine,
For whylome they haue conquerd sea and land,
Vpon the sea to wreake his fell intent;
Which afterward both sea and land possest:
The spacious Shenan spreading like a sea,
To ioyne in one, ere to the sea they come,
And after these the Sea Nymphs marched all,
Which haue the sea in charge to them assinde,
That Venus of the fomy sea was bred;
For all about that rocke the sea did flow.
That all the sea disturbed with their traine,
Till that at length nigh to the sea they drew;
And all the sea, deuided each from either:
Like as the sea (which plaine he shewed there)
The sea it selfe doest thou not plainely see
What though the sea with waues continuall
And down the rock him throwing, in the sea him dround.
With whom as he did passe by the sea shore,
Not farre in sea; of which the one appeares
And this deuouring Sea, that naught doth spare,
Into the Sea her selfe did headlong throw,
And that she did transport the same by sea,
Your brothers land the which the sea hath layd
But that the sea it to my share did lay?
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
But that the sea hath it vnto me throwne?
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
For what the mighty Sea hath once possest,
For all the shores, which to the sea accoste,
Into the sea he droue quite from that soyle,
To the sea shore he gan his way apply,
Tho when they came to the sea coast, they found
To put to sea, with whom they did compound,
Talus into the sea did forth issew,
And catching hold of this Sea-beaten chest,
There shall a Lyon from the sea-bord wood
The watry Southwinde from the seabord cost
Which all along the Southerne sea-coast lay,
Till that to the sea-coast at length she her addrest.
Thou doest the prayers of the righteous sead
Be it worthy of thy race and royall sead,
Which being ment of mortall creatures sead,
Or surely borne of some Heroicke sead,
But reason teacheth that the fruitfull seades
Who all in rage his Sea-god syre besought,
Her Sea-god syre she dearely did perswade,
and feasts the Sea-gods all.
(This Tryphon is the seagods surgeon hight)
To all the Sea-gods and their fruitfull seede,
First the Sea-gods, which to themselues doe clame
Vnder the Sea-gods seale autenticall,
But yelling Meawes, with Seagulles hoarse and bace,
His sea-horses did seeme to sport amayne,
A booke, that was both signd and seald with blood,
And virgin wex, that neuer yet was seald,
Vnder the Sea-gods seale autenticall,
So firmely she had sealed vp her brest.
For safeties sake that same his sea-marke made,
That through the seame, which did his hauberk close,
But that he must do battell with the Sea-nymphes sonne.
A Sea-nymphes sonne, that Marinell is hight,
Did search, sore grieued in her gentle brest,
By further search had passage found elsewhere,
She secretly would search each daintie lim,
They softly gan to search his griesly wound:
She made those Damzels search, which being stayd,
To search the secret haunts of Dianes company.
Through all the woods, to search from place to place,
To search the God of loue, her Nymphes she sent
To sea[r]ch her forth, where so she might be fond,
My Lord and I will search the wide forrest.
The wood they enter, and search euery where,
To search each secret of that goodly sted,
Ne could by search nor any meanes out find
And search the courses of the rowling spheares,
And earnest search, where it was kept in store
To search out those, that vsd to rob and steale,
After long search and chauff, he turned backe
But I the measure of her flight doe search,
And lighting candles new, gan search anone,
And searched euery way, through which his wings
They searched diuersely, so both diuided were.
And searched all their cels and secrets neare;
Into the hart, and searcheth euery vaine,
Searching all lands and each remotest part,
Their safetie, least by searching daungers new,
Where searching euery part, her well assured,
One day, as he was searching of their wounds,
He cast about, and searcht his balefull bookes againe.
Well searcht, eftsoones he gan apply reliefe
Then searcht his secret wounds, and made a priefe
And after hauing searcht the intuse deepe,
And euery litle limbe he searcht around,
And through his armour all his bodie seard,
His cole-blacke hands did seeme to haue beene seard
A cloud of smoothering smoke and sulphur seare
Like an old Oke whose pith and sap is seare,
My faithfull seruice, that by land and seas
Sleepe after toyle, port after stormie seas,
He cryde, as raging seas are wont to rore,
Built on a rocke adioyning to the seas:
As a tall ship tossed in troublous seas,
Better safe port, then be in seas distrest.
Of that seas nature did him not auise.
That all the seas for feare do seeme away to fly.
Sucking the seas into his entralles deepe,
Compared to the creatures in the seas entrall.
First through the Euxine seas bore all the flowr of Greece.
Thou God of winds, that raignest in the seas,
Ne durst assay to wade the perlous seas,
Proteus is Shepheard of the seas of yore,
Through all the seas so ruefully resound,
Confounds both land & seas, and skyes doth ouercast.
The huge seas vnder her t'obay her seruaunts law.
The raging seas, and makst the stormes to flie;
That rules the Seas, and makes them rise or fall;
And deckt with pearles, which th'Indian seas for her prepaire.
A God of seas through his mad mothers blame,
Through the AEgaean seas from Pirates vew,
And all the raging seas for ioy forgot to rore.
The surging seas, when they do sorest rage,
To count the seas abundant progeny,
Then to recount the Seas posterity:
For that the seas by her are most augmented.
And greedy seas doe in the spoile of life delight.
Yet loe the seas I see by often beating,
Ye Gods of seas, if any Gods at all
To none, but to the seas sole Soueraine.
Vpon your seas, he claym'd as propertie:
Which wandring on his seas imperiall,
After long tossing in the seas distrest,
From all the tempests of these worldly seas,
In seas of troubles and of toylesome paine,
The horrible Sea-satyre, that doth shew
Quite through his shield, and in his shoulder seasd,
For by no meanes the high banke he could sease,
The Monster ready on the pray to sease,
Waiting aduauntage on the pray to sease;
And on the threasure by that iudgement seased.
Spring-headed Hydraes, and sea-shouldring Whales,
But first thou must a season fast and pray,
Till season serue new passage to assay;
There when they rested had a season dew,
But the milde air with season moderate
But past awhile, when she fit season saw
Faire lawnds, to take the sunne in season dew;
And washeth Winborne meades in season drye.
One day, as she to shunne the season whot,
Agreeing well both with the place and season,
Her gentle hart, that now long season past
Vpon all which the Briton Prince made seasure,
Of which he supt so oft, that on his seat
Which fast is tyde to Ioues eternall seat?
Whose kingdomes seat Cleopolis is red,
And eke huge mountaines from their natiue seat
As they the earth would shoulder from her seat,
Where you a Saint with Saints your seat haue wonne:
That all on vprore from her settled seat
And set in highest seat of dignitee,
Whom neither wind out of their seat could forse,
And in the midst thereof a siluer seat,
Whom fortune hath alreadie laid in lowest seat.
Which blot his sonne succeeding in his seat,
And striues to mount vnto his natiue seat;
That the weake soule her seat did yet retaine,
Out of his wauering seat him pluckt perforse,
To sit in second seat of soueraigne king,
To be the compasse of his kingdomes seat:
But finding no fit seat, the lifelesse corse it left.
But he was mounted in his seat so high,
Vpon Ioues iudgement seat wayt day and night,
Sith in th'Almighties euerlasting seat
And to her kingdomes seat restore agayne;
But vertues seat is deepe within the mynd,
That to the folds, where sheepe at night doe seat,
To trouble my still seate, and heapes of pretious pelfe.
A seate in Ireland safely to remayne,
Which him before, that sacred seate did fill,
To sit in his owne seate, his cause to end,
In seate of iudgement, in th'Almighties stead,
And it was seated in an Island strong,
And her before was seated ouerthwart
They all attonce out of their seates arose,
And shadie seates, and sundry flowring bankes,
Seauen women by him slaine, and eaten clene.
And leaue his loue in that sea-walled fort.
Ne lesse did Talus suffer sleepe to seaze
Tho all in rage, he on him streight did seaze,
Such one was Gluttony, the second of that crew.
The second was as Almner of the place,
And to my tunes thy second tenor rayse,
When gentle Vna saw the second fall
Of second sister, who did far excell
For both did at their second sister grutch,
Pyrrochles gan reply the second time,
Thence brought th[m] to the second roome, whose wals
The second Brute, the second both in name,
The second Brute, the second both in name,
They crownd the second Constantine with ioyous teares,
The second Bulwarke was the Hearing sence,
Gainst which the second troupe dessignment makes;
And gan himselfe to second battell bend,
A second fall redoubling backe againe.
The second was Parlante, a bold knight,
Faire Amoretta in the second place:
The second was an holy Nunne to chose,
To sit in second seat of soueraigne king,
Both first and second Troy shall dare to equalise.
This second Hellene, faire Dame Hellenore,
Till that againe the second euening
Then when the second watch was almost past,
The second Dyamond, the youngest Triamond.
The second was to Triamond behight,
Vnto the second best, that lou'd her better;
Hath conquered you anew in second fight:
Her second care, though in another kind;
Thence forth I passed to the second gate,
Art playing second natures part, supplyed it.
It seem'd a second paradise to ghesse,
The second had to name Sir Bellisont,
But second vnto none in prowesse prayse;
The second day, so soone as morrow light
The second not so strong but wise, Decetto;
He stayd his second strooke, and did his hand abase.
And with the second stroke, thought certainely
Her selfe sole left, a second spoyle to bee
Shun secresie, and talke in open sight:
Some secret ill, or hidden foe of his:
In secret anguish and vnpittied plaint,
Those two he tooke, and in a secret bed,
Who soone him brought into a secret part,
And scorching Sunne does dry my secret vaines:
In secret shadow, farre from all mens sight:
And learned had to loue with secret lookes,
Lo his Fidessa to thy secret faith I flye.
And bad say on the secret of her hart.
Who all that while lay hid in secret shade:
Of whom he learned had in secret wise
The saluage nation feele her secret smart,
So long in secret cabin there he held
And all her wit in secret counsels spent,
In secret shadow by a fountaine side:
In secret shadow, all this to behold,
Some secret sorrow did her heart distraine:
And secret poyson through their inner parts,
Whose secret filth good manners biddeth not be told.
The secret meaning of th'eternall might,
Ah curteous knight (quoth she) what secret wound
The secret cause of his perplexitie:
That ere one be aware, by secret stealth
And in his conscience made a secret breach,
Or other secret vertue did ensew;
The secret treasons, which of late I know
And sacred lampe in secret chamber hide,
Himselfe he frees by secret meanes vnseene;
Her voluntarie paine, and feele some secret ease.
And now he doth himselfe in secret shrowd,
And tell the secret of your mortall smart;
Their bloud with secret filth infected hath,
But know, that secret vertues are infusd
As fearefull fowle, that long in secret caue
And told for secret how he vnderstood
Me leading, in a secret corner layd,
In secret shadow from the sunny ray,
Ne can be quencht, within my secret bowels bee.
Then searcht his secret wounds, and made a priefe
To see his secret store.
Whereas he sitting found in secret shade
But safe I haue them kept in secret mew,
What secret place (quoth he) can safely hold
Haue secret powre, t'appease inflamed rage:
By secret wayes, that none might it espy,
That in the secret of your hart close lyes,
Which seeth with secret fire eternally,
Yet secret pleasure did offence empeach,
And oft of secret ill bids vs beware:
His stubborne brest gan secret pleasaunce to embrace.
The secret signes of kindled lust appeare,
In secret shade, after long wanton ioyes:
For not thy fault, but secret powre vnseene,
The secret vertue of that weapon keene,
Now leading him into a secret shade
And ioyd his loue in secret vnespyde.
Way to her loue, and secret darts did throw;
Where she for secret purpose did appoynt
Such secret ease felt gentle Britomart,
Ne ought in secret from the same remaynd;
To let the secret of her hart to her appeare.
Through deepe impression of thy secret might,
As if ought in this world in secret store
Of secret foes, that him shall make in mischiefe fall.
Where they in secret counsell close conspird,
Couered with secret cloud of silent night,
Finding the Nymph a sleepe in secret wheare,
She did enuy that soueraigne salue, in secret store.
With so sweet sence and secret power vnspide,
To search the secret haunts of Dianes company.
To lurke emongst your Nymphes in secret wize;
There yet, some say, in secret he does ly,
In secret wize her selfe thence to withdraw,
She with her brings into a secret Ile,
Had she not fled into a secret mew,
Infixt such secret sting of greedy lust,
He rou'd at her, and told his secret care:
By such close signes they secret way did make
And seest euery secret of the mind;
His secret drift, till he her layd abord.
Suffred, these seuen monethes day in secret den
To search each secret of that goodly sted,
Of secret daunger, ne let sleepe oppresse
In secret shade, and saw both first and last,
Out of her secret stand, that day for to out weare.
And euery one gan grow in secret dout
Which was not yet so secret, but some part
His hart with secret enuie gan to swell,
Did priuily put coles vnto his secret fire.
As if they secret counsels did partake;
And euery secret worke of natures wayes,
Still watcht on euery side, of secret foes affrayd.
Of secret things, and all the powres of nature,
Through secret vnderstanding of their feature.
Come see the secret of the life of man,
Through secret feeling of his generous spright,
And secret feare, to see their fatall fine,
Saluagesse sans finesse, shewing secret wit.
And left behind her in her secret bowre,
As guilefull Goldsmith that by secret skill,
And fell away, as feeling secret blame.
And touched was with secret wrath and shame
His powrelesse arme benumbd with secret feare
For sudden ioy, and secret feare withall,
Which secret fate hath in this Ladie wrought,
But Artegall close smyling ioy'd in secret hart.
Thenceforth I sought by secret meanes to worke
Yet weend by secret signes of manlinesse,
And by his persons secret seemlyhed
By casting secret flakes of lustfull fire
Of his old loue, conceau'd in secret brest,
Did neede to gard from force, or secret theft
The secret cause and nature of his teene,
Ne lesse was she in secret hart affected,
And suffred all his secret marke to see:
Gan cast a secret liking to this captiue straunge.
Vnto her selfe in secret she did call
Say on (quoth he) the secret of your hart:
Such secret comfort, and such heauenly pleasures,
Being vnarm'd, and set in secret shade.
Gan mutter close a certaine secret charme,
But she whose sides before with secret wound
Or secret guifts so with his keepers wrought,
Mote not bewray the secret of her lode,
Where euer yet I be, my secrete aid
And all things secrete wisely could bewray,
At sight thereof abasht with secrete shame,
But he them spotted with reproch, or secrete shame.
And in his bosome secretly there lay
Her hollow womb did secretly inspire,
Proceeded, yet each one felt secretly
Lurckt false Duessa secretly vnseene,
That secretly doth vs procure to fall,
She secretly would search each daintie lim,
That secretly he saw, yet note discoure:
Yet secretly their hoste did on them lowre,
Past through his eyes, and secretly did glyde
But secretly from thence that night her bore away.
With guilefull loue did secretly agree,
And secretly his enemies did slay:
Did secretly out of her prison steale;
But to her selfe it secretly retayned,
And secretly afflict with iealous feare,
But that some life remayned secretly,
Ne secretly from thought of fell reuenge surceasse.
And sawst the secrets of the world vnmade,
You to inquere the secrets of my griefe,
Vtterers of secrets he from thence debard,
And dared of all sinnes the secrets to vnfold.
For how canst thou those greater secrets know,
And all the secrets of their entrayles sought.
And searched all their cels and secrets neare;
Him heedlesse bit, the whiles he was thereof secure.
But all the while the fisher did securely sleepe.
Securely he did after him pursew,
Your treasure here in some securitie,
But did in safe securitie abide,
That when he sleepes in most security,
Where he is shrowded in security.
Yet spake she seldom, but thought more, the lesse she sed.
Then brought he forth Sedition, breeding stryfe
Fild with false rumors and seditious trouble,
Who with her forged beautie did seduce
Where plaine none might her see, nor she see any plaine.
Where plaine none might her see, nor she see any plaine.
His Lady sad to see his sore constraint,
To see th'vnkindly Impes of heauen accurst,
Who see your vanquisht foes before you lye:
All cleane dismayd to see so vncouth sight,
Who all in rage to see his skilfull might
Come see, where your false Lady doth her honour staine.
Then gan she waile and weepe, to see that woefull stowre.
Art thou misshaped thus, as now I see?
To loue this gentle Lady, whom ye see,
I chaunst to see her in her proper hew,
Were hidd in water, that I could not see,
When such I see, that all for pittie I could die.
And sad to see her sorrowfull constraint
They had not ridden farre, when they might see
What doe I see? what hard mishap is this,
Amased stands, her selfe so mockt to see
Long with her traueild, till at last they see
Why they were come, her royall state to see,
Still as he rode, he gnasht his teeth, to see
Of reasons rule, to see this recreant knight,
Ioyous, to see his ymage in mine eye,
The warlike feates of both those knights to see.
